  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Tag wrangling is a curation practice in which volunteer editors organize a folksonomy by designating canonical tags, linking synonyms, and creating grouping relationships — without restricting what users can tag at the point of creation. The practice was developed and named by Archive of Our Own (AO3), a fanfiction archive launched in 2009, and represents one of the most successful real-world syntheses of free tagging and controlled vocabulary.\nAO3 uses six distinct tag types (ratings, archive warnings, categories, fandoms, relationships, characters, and freeform/additional tags). Users can enter any freeform text as a tag. Tag wranglers — a distributed team of volunteers — then organize the resulting namespace through three operations. First, they designate canonical tags as the preferred form for each concept: \u0026ldquo;Sherlock Holmes/John Watson\u0026rdquo; becomes the canonical form that \u0026ldquo;Johnlock\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;Holmes/Watson\u0026rdquo; redirect to. Second, they link synonyms to their canonical form so that searching either term finds content tagged with any variant. Third, they create metatags that group related-but-not-synonymous concepts — a metatag for \u0026ldquo;Coffee Shop AUs\u0026rdquo; might gather freeform tags like \u0026ldquo;barista AU\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;coffeehouse romance\u0026rdquo; under a common umbrella.\n",
